Brent Crude is currently at just over $35 a barrel. News today that OPEC+ could not reach an agreement on production cuts and that Saudi Arabia and Russia both pledged to increase production has caused prices to crash. Both countries claim they can win the oil price war on the horizon. Additionally, COVID-19 is spreading rapidly throughout the world including Italy, South Korea, and the USA. The virus shows no signs of slowing, especially before March 31st. In the last five years, Brent Crude has been above $63 a barrel for only 9/60 months and only once on March 31st.

Saudi Arabia has started a price war after Russia refused OPECs plan to cut production in response to corona virus outbreak. The Saudi's reduced the cost of the crude oil they sell to foreign markets by the most in 20 years. As reported by Bloomberg, it is a shock and awe strategy, an effort to bring Russia back to the negotiating table. Prices are being slashed by $6-8 per barrel.

The current price of Brent Oil as of 7 March 2020 is $53 dollars per barrel. Oil was last above $63 in early January based on the likelihood of reduced trade disputes between the US and China lifting global growth. The current depressed price reflects the growing global pandemic (COVID-19). May options (CME) are settling below $50 with only outliers showing a price of $63 (so if it does rebound quickly that is a big payout to whoever bought those call options). Between reduced travel hitting jet fuel demands to reduced travel hitting gas prices, oil will continue to stay low until fears of the pandemic subside or OPEC gets involved. Even if OPEC cuts production further it is unlikely to produce a 18.89% price change within three weeks.
Brent crude is down about 30 per cent since January.

The Organisation of the Petroleum Exporting Countries and its allies meet today in Vienna. In December, they announced production cuts of 1.7m barrels a day, to brace themselves for booming production in not just America, a perpetual headache, but Brazil, Guyana and Norway. Those cuts now look woefully insufficient. The spread of covid-19 pushed the price of Brent crude below $50 a barrel during the course of the day on February 28th. Saudi Arabia is among the OPEC producers keen to raise prices quickly—the IMF estimates that the kingdom needs oil at $83.60 to balance its budget. Russia, which has allied itself with the cartel since 2016, has habitually opposed output cuts, only to agree to them at the last moment. To date the benefits of increased influence and business dealings with OPEC members have trumped complaints about production limits from Russia’s oil companies. Saudi Arabia is among those hoping that logic still holds in Vienna. —————- COMMENT: Time to go low!

The Energy Information Agency (EIA) has estimated that the price of Brent crude oil will average $58 per barrel in the first half of 2020 before rising to an average of $64 per barrel in the final 6 months of 2020. The EIA has made this forecast based on the expectation that inventories (i.e. supply) of oil increased in 2020 and will decrease in 2021. The EIA’s forecast does not include any disruptions to oil supply (which would most likely increase the price of Brent crude oil).

Update of forecast obtained by applying 'forecast' function from R package of the same name to monthly time series (last close) scraped from eia.gov, with manual addition of data point for January 31, 2020, while we wait for EIA to update their series. FWIW, the algorithm selected an exponential smoothing model with a multiplicative error term, an additive trend, and no seasonality, and the point forecast for end of March is $58.75. Will update again not later than early March, possibly sooner with a weekly model if there's a lot of movement in one direction in the first couple of weeks of February.

Brent oil prices have gradually increased since October 2019 following heightened geopolitical risk in the Middle East; specifically, attacks on Saudi oil infrastructure, increased conflict risk between the U.S. and Iran, in addition to heightened domestic sociopolitical risks in Iraq. Most recently, in the Mediterranean, France, Germany, Italy, Greece, Cyprus, Turkey and Russia contend over the formation of a new government in Libya - as well as its hydrocarbon riches. Libya's National Oil Corporation (NOC) shut down two oilfields after forces loyal to Haftar closed a pipeline, raising Brent prices to $65.22 on 20 Jan 2020.

Oil prices on both sides of the Atlantic have been edging higher although the relatively sluggish Chinese economic growth (compared to their own historical growth) weighed on futures as China is the world’s largest crude importer. There is significant political pressure to keep oil prices down during the 2020 US elections which will likely result in Middle East policies favoring lower prices.

The balance of factors points to oil prices staying where they are in the short to near term – in line with Brent Crude futures which point to a$64 price level at end March. The factors likely to notably change the price are not likely to manifest till later in the year. At the margin, oil prices seem more likely to fall to below $63 than rise above $69: the current price of $65 is closer to the lower boundary than the upper boundary and the IEA has predicted that non-OPEC production is likely to increase through this year which could put downward pressure on the price. However, there remain risks which could provoke upward pressure: geopolitical tension leading to potential supply shocks remains elevated post the Iran-US incidents; the Fed’s interest rate cuts and trade deal progress could improve demand.

It is well-known that oil prices are sensitive to the global economy and geopolitical events, especially in the volatile Middle East. As the political situation stabilizes, oil prices tend to go back to their underlying pre-jolt values. (This is my view anyway.)
